+# Double-Agent TDD
+
+## Overview
+
+D.U.H. supports a strict **red-green-refactor** flow driven by *two* cooperating agents — a **Driver** and a **Navigator** — pair-programming through the classic TDD cycle. The authoritative design document is [ADR-076](../adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md).
+
+The feature exists because the single-agent "just ask for TDD" pattern reliably fails: the same model writes the test *and* the implementation in one assistant turn, so the RED step — the whole reason TDD works — never actually fails. The double-agent flow fixes this by gating every phase on a **real subprocess test-run**. The model cannot decide what "failing" means; the harness does.
+
+## Roles
+
+| Role          | Agent overlay | Tool access per phase             | Responsibility                               |
+|---------------|--------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
+| **Driver**    | `coder`       | Full tools (Read / Edit / Write / Bash)  | Writes the failing test, writes the minimum code to pass it, applies the Navigator's refactor. |
+| **Navigator** | `reviewer`    | `tool_choice="none"` during SPEC and REFACTOR_PLAN; full tools during VALIDATE | Drafts the test spec, proposes refactors, validates the final state. |
+
+Both agents are just `Engine` instances with different system prompts (ADR-012). There is no new provider, no new tool layer, no new runtime — everything reuses the existing kernel abstractions. That means every capability you already have (MCP servers, hooks, permissions, plan mode, etc.) works inside `/tdd` and `duh tdd` without modification.
+
+## The six phases
+
+The flow is a strict state machine. Every transition is guarded; out-of-order calls raise `ValueError`.
+
+```
+EMPTY  ─▶ SPEC  ─▶ RED  ─▶ GREEN  ─▶ REFACTOR_PLAN  ─▶ REFACTOR_APPLY  ─▶ DONE
+   ▲                │
+   └─ RED unexpectedly passes (spec too loose → Navigator re-drafts)
+```
+
+| # | Phase            | Actor     | Gate                                               |
+|---|------------------|-----------|----------------------------------------------------|
+| 1 | `SPEC`           | Navigator | Spec text non-empty.                               |
+| 2 | `RED`            | Driver    | Test command exits **non-zero** (failing test is success). |
+| 3 | `GREEN`          | Driver    | Test command exits **zero**.                       |
+| 4 | `REFACTOR_PLAN`  | Navigator | Plan text non-empty.                               |
+| 5 | `REFACTOR_APPLY` | Driver    | Refactor plan was present (can't apply nothing).   |
+| 6 | `VALIDATE`       | Navigator | Test command exits **zero**.                       |
+
+The RED/GREEN asymmetry is the heart of TDD: a test that passes at RED means the spec doesn't actually discriminate the feature. The harness short-circuits back to `EMPTY` and the Navigator is invited to tighten the spec. The `spec_revisions` counter is observable via `/tdd status` or `TddMode.spec_revisions` for telemetry.
+
+## CLI — `duh tdd`
+
+One-shot, non-interactive, intended for CI or "I have 10 minutes, ship it" sessions:
+
+```bash
+duh tdd "<feature description>"
+```
+
+### Flags
+
+| Flag | Default | Purpose |
+|---|---|---|
+| `--test "<cmd>"` | `pytest -x --no-header` | Test command run at each gate. Shell-split with `shlex`. |
+| `--driver-model <name>` | same as `--model` | Override the Driver's model (tier alias OK). |
+| `--navigator-model <name>` | same as `--model` | Override the Navigator's model. |
+| `--model`, `--provider`, `--max-turns`, `--debug`, … | inherited from global `duh` flags | standard plumbing |
+
+### Example
+
+```bash
+duh tdd --test "pytest tests/unit/test_cache.py -x" \
+        --driver-model medium --navigator-model small \
+        "LRU cache drops the oldest entry when full"
+```
+
+Sample output (abbreviated):
+
+```
+duh tdd — provider=anthropic driver=claude-sonnet-4-6 navigator=claude-haiku-4-5
+  test command: pytest tests/unit/test_cache.py -x
+  feature     : LRU cache drops the oldest entry when full
+
+== SPEC (navigator) ==
+== RED (driver) ==
+  [RED gate ✓] exit=1 gate_passed=True
+== GREEN (driver) ==
+  [GREEN gate ✓] exit=0 gate_passed=True
+== REFACTOR_PLAN (navigator) ==
+== REFACTOR_APPLY (driver) ==
+== VALIDATE (navigator) ==
+  [VALIDATE gate ✓] exit=0 gate_passed=True
+
+TDD state: DONE
+  feature: LRU cache drops the oldest entry when full
+  ...
+```
+
+### Exit codes
+
+| Exit | Meaning |
+|---|---|
+| 0 | `TddState.DONE` — all six phases passed. |
+| 1 | Flow did not reach DONE (gate failure, or spec was revised and the run ended before re-approval). |
+| 4 | `PROVIDER_ERROR` — no API key / auth available. |
+
+## REPL — `/tdd`
+
+Inside `duh` (interactive REPL or TUI):
+
+```text
+/tdd <feature>            # run the full six-phase flow inline
+/tdd status               # show the flow wiring + default test command
+/tdd help                 # full syntax
+```
+
+`/tdd <feature>` is implemented as a REPL lifecycle signal (same mechanism `/plan` uses). The REPL builds a Driver + Navigator as lightweight sibling Engines of the active session and streams phase / gate events inline. Tool calls made by the Driver (Edit, Write, Bash, …) go through the same approval + audit plumbing as normal REPL turns.
+
+## Python API
+
+```python
+from duh.kernel.deps import Deps
+from duh.kernel.engine import Engine, EngineConfig
+from duh.kernel.tdd_mode import TddMode
+
+driver = Engine(
+    deps=Deps(call_model=my_provider.stream, run_tool=executor.run, approve=approver.check),
+    config=EngineConfig(model="claude-sonnet-4-6", system_prompt=coder_prompt, tools=tools),
+)
+navigator = Engine(
+    deps=Deps(call_model=my_provider.stream, run_tool=executor.run, approve=approver.check),
+    config=EngineConfig(model="claude-haiku-4-5", system_prompt=reviewer_prompt, tools=tools),
+)
+
+tdd = TddMode(
+    driver=driver,
+    navigator=navigator,
+    test_command=["pytest", "-x", "tests/unit/test_cache.py"],
+)
+
+async for event in tdd.run_all("LRU cache drops oldest entry"):
+    print(event)
+
+assert tdd.state.name == "DONE"
+```
+
+`TddMode` exposes one coroutine per phase (`draft_spec`, `red`, `green`, `propose_refactor`, `refactor_apply`, `validate`) and two convenience drivers (`refactor`, `run_all`). Every coroutine is an async generator yielding the same event dicts the `Engine` yields, plus two new types:
+
+| Event type    | Keys                                                          | Fires                  |
+|---------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------|
+| `tdd_phase`   | `phase`, `actor`                                              | Entry to each phase.   |
+| `tdd_gate`    | `phase`, `passed`, `test_passed`, `exit_code`, `stdout`, `stderr` | After the gate runs.   |
+
+For tests, you can swap in a `test_runner` callable (signature `(cmd, cwd) -> GateResult`) so unit tests don't shell out. See `tests/unit/test_tdd_mode.py` for the pattern.
+
+## Design decisions
+
+See [ADR-076](../adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md) for the full context, alternatives considered, and acceptance criteria. In brief:
+
+- **Two Engines, not one** — a single Engine with a system-prompt switch per phase conflates roles; the Navigator has to re-read what the Driver wrote from disk, not recall it from shared context, and that's where the review value comes from.
+- **Gate is external to the model** — the single biggest failure mode of the "just ask for TDD" flow is the model skipping the RED-must-fail check. Putting the check in a subprocess call the harness controls (not a tool the model can choose to skip) is the only reliable fix.
+- **Reuse existing abstractions** — Driver = `Engine` with `coder` overlay; Navigator = `Engine` with `reviewer` overlay; state machine = same shape as `PlanMode`. Zero new infrastructure.
+
+## See also
+
+- [ADR-076: Double-Agent TDD Flow](../adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md) — the contract between Driver and Navigator.
+- [Multi-Agent Guide](Multi-Agent.md) — how agent overlays work in general.
+- [ADR-012: Multi-Agent](../adrs/ADR-012-multi-agent.md) — why agents are just Engines.
+- `duh/kernel/tdd_mode.py` — the implementation.
+- `tests/unit/test_tdd_mode.py` — the six-phase contract test suite.
